---
import BaseLayout from "../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
import TimeLineElement from "../components/cv/TimeLine.astro";
---

<BaseLayout title="Resume" sideBarActiveItemID="cv">

  <div class="mb-5">
    <div class="text-3xl w-full font-bold">Education</div>
  </div>

  <div class="time-line-container grid gap-4 mb-10">
    <TimeLineElement
      title="M.S. in Applied Health Behavioral Research"
      subtitle="Sep 2023 - Aug 2024 at Washington University in St. Louis School of Medicine, St. Louis, MO"
    >
      GPA: 4.00/4.00<br/>
      Thesis: Altered Functional Connectivity and Emotion Regulation in Children with Early Sensory Challenges<br/>
      Mentor: Dr. Rebecca Schwarzlose, Assistant Professor
    </TimeLineElement>
    <TimeLineElement
      title="B.A. in Psychology and Communication (Graduated with Honors)"
      subtitle="Sep 2018 - Jun 2022 at University of California, Davis, Davis, CA"
    >
      GPA: 3.918/4.00
    </TimeLineElement>
  </div>

  <div class="mb-5">
    <div class="text-3xl w-full font-bold">Research Experience</div>
  </div>

  <div class="time-line-container mb-10">
    <TimeLineElement
      title="Neurodevelopment of Naturalistic Social/Emotion Encoding and Emotion Regulation"
      subtitle="Jun 2024 - Present at Washington University School of Medicine (Dr. Cat Camacho, Dr. Rebecca Schwarzlose)"
    >
      • Characterized neonatal thalamus to visual cortex functional (fMRI) and structural (DTI) connectivity patterns and assessed individual differences in relation to social looking behaviors at age 1 year<br/>
      • Developed encoding models of contextualized emotional, semantic, and audio-visual stimuli (movies) across development from fMRI data of 620 children ages 5-15<br/>
      • Characterized associations between individual cortical selectivity maps and emotion regulation strategies using machine learning<br/>
      • Developed pilot study for behavioral and neural naturalistic emotion regulation during peer interactions using DOT
    </TimeLineElement>
    <TimeLineElement
      title="Clinical and Neural Correlates of Sensory Over-responsivity in Childhood"
      subtitle="Aug 2023 - Jun 2025 at Washington University School of Medicine (Dr. Rebecca Schwarzlose, Dr. Chad Sylvester)"
    >
      • Identified differences in resting-state functional connectivity patterns associated with sensory over-responsivity through multi-level regression using multiple neuroimaging datasets<br/>
      • Synthesized clinical symptom data across 5 national data consortiums (n=15,000) to characterize symptom presentation differences<br/>
      • Characterized phenotypic heterogeneity in subcortical volume among preadolescents with autistic traits using hierarchical mixed-effects models<br/>
      • Assessed the development of emotion regulation strategies in children with early-onset sensory challenges
    </TimeLineElement>
    <TimeLineElement
      title="Emotion Regulation and Sleep Bruxism"
      subtitle="Sep 2022 - Jul 2023 at Stanford University (Dr. Sylvia Kreibig, Dr. James Gross)"
    >
      • Analyzed actigraphy and polysomnography recordings from 300 participants to quantify associations between rhythmic masticatory muscle activity and emotion regulation capabilities<br/>
      • Conducted extensive literature reviews on sleep bruxism, emotion regulation, and physiological measures
    </TimeLineElement>
    <TimeLineElement
      title="Smoking Behaviors and Cognitive Control"
      subtitle="Sep 2021 - Mar 2022 at University of California, Davis (Dr. Shelley Blozis)"
    >
      • Analyzed national public health data (MIDUS2) to examine how smoking behavior impacts self-reported impulsivity and emotional control
    </TimeLineElement>
  </div>

